<paragraph id="8BD4368AFF9FAB5962FC4331FD371C6B" blockId="11.[192,1440,1808,1929]" lastBlockId="12.[192,1440,217,338]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E62FC4331FE951A11" bold="true" box="[192,278,1808,1832]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Notes.</emphasis>
This specimen was identified and labeled by P. Hurd as 
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E61F44330FC581A11" box="[968,987,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">X</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6B4D09FF9FAB5E61D54331FEC91A71" authority="Cockerell (1912: 492)" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityPageNumber="492" authorityYear="1912" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="varians" subGenus="Schonnherria" variety="piurensis">
(
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E61CE4331FB871A1E" box="[1010,1028,1808,1831]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">S</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E66274330FBFB1A11" box="[1051,1144,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">varians</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E668A4330FAA51A11" box="[1206,1318,1809,1832]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">piurensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFA4B7BFF9FAB5E67114331FEC91A71" author="Cockerell, T. D. A." pageId="11" pageNumber="10" pagination="484 - 494" refId="ref11079" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. 1912. Descriptions and records of bees-XLVII. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 8 (10): 484 - 494." type="journal article" year="1912">Cockerell (1912: 492)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a form originally described from material collected at Piura in northwestern Peru outside the Amazon basin. Additional manuscript notes from Hurd accompanying the specimens of this species in the 
<collectionCode id="ED7AAE4FFF9FAB5E63304350FEE21AB0" box="[268,353,1905,1929]" collectionName="USA, Washington D.C., National Museum of Natural History, [formerly, United States National Museum]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" type="Museum">USNM</collectionCode>
collection indicate that Hurd viewed 
<taxonomicName id="4C6B4D09FF9FAB5E61184350FC511AB1" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1874" box="[804,978,1904,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varians" subGenus="Schonnherria">
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF9FAB5E61184350FC511AB1" box="[804,978,1904,1928]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">X. (S.) varians</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species complex that may involve multiple species-level taxa. A more comprehensive revisionary treatment of this group is outside the scope of the present paper. From the other Amazon basin species of subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C6B4D09FF98AB59664C44D8FA941C28" authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[1136,1303,249,273]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Schonnherria">
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF98AB59664C44D8FA941C28" box="[1136,1303,249,273]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Schonnherria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6B4D09FF98AB5962FC453BFEF31C08" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1874" box="[192,368,282,305]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Xylocopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varians" subGenus="Schonnherria">
<emphasis id="B91FEA98FF98AB5962FC453BFEF31C08" box="[192,368,282,305]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">X. (S.) varians</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be identified by the combination of dark dorsal pubescence, blue dorsal iridescence, and white lateral setae on the metatarsi.
</paragraph>
